<section class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-inner">
        <div class="faq-left">
            <p class="titan-section-label">COMMON QUESTIONS</p>
            <h2 class="faq-heading">Utah FERS Planning FAQ</h2>
            <p class="faq-sub">Answers specific to Utah federal employees and FERS benefits.</p>
            <a href="/contact/" class="resources-cta">Ask a FERS Specialist</a>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-right">
            <div class="faq-accordion">
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">When can I retire under FERS with full benefits?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">You can retire with immediate annuity at your Minimum Retirement Age (MRA) with 30 years of service, age 60 with 20 years, or age 62 with 5 years. Retiring at MRA with 10-29 years results in a 5% per year reduction until age 62.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">How does Utah tax my federal pension and TSP withdrawals?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Utah taxes federal pensions and TSP withdrawals as ordinary income at the 4.85% flat rate. However, Utah offers a retirement tax credit for seniors that can reduce or eliminate state tax on retirement income.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">Should I contribute to traditional or Roth TSP?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">It depends on your current tax bracket and expected retirement taxes. Generally, traditional TSP makes sense if you're in the 22% bracket or higher. Roth TSP can be beneficial for younger employees or those expecting higher retirement tax rates.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">What is the special retirement supplement and how does it work?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">The supplement approximates your Social Security benefit until you're eligible at 62. It's only for employees retiring at MRA with 30+ years or special provision employees. It has earning limits — you lose $1 for every $2 earned over about $22,320 annually.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">When should I drop my FEGLI coverage?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">FEGLI becomes very expensive after age 65 as it converts to decreasing coverage. Many retirees drop it at 65 and buy term life insurance if still needed, or switch to whole life for estate planning. We analyze your specific situation to determine timing.</div>
                </button>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>